s reason I also highly recommend this book\n("},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"amongst others"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://github.com/coderbyheart/first-principles/issues/19","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":")\nas a must read in my talks and to whomever asks for a book recommendation on\nsoftware architecture."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Since this year I am in the lucky situation to grow my team that and having\nrecently hired a Junior engineer, REST in Practice is one of the first books I\nordered."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"This is a good opportunity to give it a second read, and review it from the\npoint of view of a team that develops software using serverless technologies, in\nTypeScript on Node.js and provide a reading guide for them that helps to\nnavigate some of the outdated sections. I will also highlight especially\nimportant chapters."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[],"tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","focusable":"false","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#still-highly-relevant","ariaLabel":"still highly relevant permalink","className":["anchor","before"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Still highly relevant"}],"tagName":"h2","properties":{"id":"still-highly-relevant","style":"position:relative;"},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Overall, the sentiment of the book still holds very true today. We need to build\nresilient, decoupled systems that can handle unpredictable load patterns. The\nbook does a very good job of showing how all of this can be achieved with a\nubiquitous communication protocol: HTTP. This principle is truly language- and\nplatform-neutral which makes it so universally applicable."}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[],"tagName":"path","properties":{"fillRule":"evenodd","d":"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z"},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"svg","properties":{"ariaHidden":"true","focusable":"false","height":"16","version":"1.1","viewBox":"0 0 16 16","width":"16"},"type":"element"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"#reading-guide","ariaLabel":"reading guide permalink","className":["anchor","before"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Reading guide"}],"tagName":"h2","properties":{"id":"reading-guide","style":"position:relative;"},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"This is my recommended reading guide for the book:"}],"tagName":"p","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 12 - Building the Case for the Web (p. 407):"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nthis is the "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"tl;dr"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" of the book, and it gives a good summary of "},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"why"}],"tagName":"em","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" the\ntechniques explained in the book work so well."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 1 - The Web As a Platform for Building Distributed Systems:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nread fully"}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 2 - Introducing Restbucks: How to GET a Coffee, Web Style:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nread fully"}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 3 - Basic Web Integration:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nskip URI tunneling and POX (p. 37-55)"}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 4 - CRUD Web Services:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nread fully, important chapter on how to properly employ HTTP for building\nAPIs"}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 5 - Hypermedia Services:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nread full! This is also an important chapter on how to make services\ndiscoverable. While the use of XML is quite clunky for a Node.js developer,\nit does not get too much in the way of the content that explains the main\nidea. After this chapter we could have a look at\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"JSON-LD"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://json-ld.org/","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 6 - Scaling Out:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nready fully, important chapter on the usefulness of caching and how to use\ncached response to reduce latency and infrastructure costs."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 7 - The Atom Syndication Format:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\ngood explanation of how to decouple microservices and allow consuming\nservices to observe changes. Skip the Java implementation part (p.207-234).\nMissing in this chapter is a push notification capability. The communication\nrelies on consumers to poll for changes, and this is very inefficient.\nMicroservices should publish events in a way that allows consumers to react\nto these changes when they happen, but only IF they happen. This is possible\nin HTTP with websockets and should be discussed after reading this chapter."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 8 - Atom Publishing Protocol:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nread, but skip the implementation guide (p. 269-283). It's a lot of XML\nthat's thrown at the reader but the underlying idea is still worth exploring:\nwe want a language-independent way to describe which actions a service\nprovides. The authors pick AtomPub as a general purpose syntax. After this\nchapter we could have a look at\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Hydra"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.markus-lanthaler.com/hydra/","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":" or\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Apache Thrift"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://thrift.apache.org/","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 9 - Web Security:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nread, but skip the OpenID and OAuth part (p. 295-339) because they are often\nnot relevant in machine-to-machine scenarios. The first and the last pages of\nthe chapter however are a good refresher on HTTP security essentials."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 10 - Semantics:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nOptional. Be aware that the solutions proposed are quite outdated, but we\nface the main question today nevertheless: How can we build a ubiquitous\nlanguages into our systems that transcends the boundaries of our business. I\nhaven't seen this to be really relevant in my day to day job."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Chapter 11 - The Web and and WS-*:"},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\nSkip. This is a discussion around specific technologies which is only\nrelevant to people who use them; which we are not."}],"tagName":"li","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"\n"}],"tagName":"ol","properties":{},"type":"element"}],"type":"root","data":{"quirksMode":false}},"frontmatter":{"title":"REST in Practice - a reading guide","subtitle":"Book review","noheadline":null,"date":"2022-07-16T16:00:00.000Z","abstract":"While the book was published in 2010 and some of its contents have not aged well, it still provides a lot of things to learn. In this post I will give my recommendations on which sections are a must read, and which ones can be skipped in case you are-like me-not very fond of Java and XML.","lang":null},"headings":[{"id":"still-highly-relevant","depth":2,"value":"Still highly relevant"},{"id":"reading-guide","depth":2,"value":"Reading guide"}]}},"Footer":{"id":"cfe5b9e2-511c-5615-992a-dab82e1f8ed7","name":"Footer","relativeDirectory":"","relativePath":"Footer.md","remark":{"htmlAst":{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Software Crafter building üå©Ô∏è cloud-based cellular IoT solutions at\n"},{"children":[{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"Nordic Semiconductor"}],"tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://nordicsemi.com/","target":"_blank","rel":["nofollow","noreferrer"]},"type":"element"},{"children":[],"type":"text","value":"."},{"children":[],"tagName":"br","properties":{},"type":"element"},{"children